   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="name-list">
            <ab type="name" n="Asmāʾ-اسماء">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn1"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Asm-Vol-4-A_F" n="اسماء">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e16-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Asmāʾ-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">اسماء</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Asmāʾ</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>ʿAbdullah (6)’s daughter, Qays (6)’s mother, slave<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn2"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Musʿab,nasab, 92</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn3"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>6thC CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn4"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn2" n="2"> In Arabic – اخذة (the taken one). She was from Khaybar and was married to a Qurayshī of the Banū al-Muṭṭalib b. Manāf. For more details about that see Lecker, JSAI 10 (1987) 24.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn3" n="3"> On this family see Introduction 6.1.2.1.. </note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn4" n="4"> Found in a genealogical list, see Introduction 8.3.3.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Barrah-برة">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn5"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Barrah-Vol-4-A_F" n="برة">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e68-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Barrah-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">برة</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Barrah</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Samuel (33)’s daughter, Ṣafīya (1)’s mother, Rifāʿa (3)’s sister</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ṭabarī, iii, 2452</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn6"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>6thC CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn7"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn6" n="2"> This family is described by Ṭabarī as من بني اسرائل (of the children of Israel), see Introduction 6.1.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn7" n="3"> Mentioned in a genealogy, see Introdution 8.3.3.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Khālida-خاللدة">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn8"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Khlida-Vol-4-A_F" n="خاللدة">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e111-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Khālida-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">خاللدة</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Khālida</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Ḥārith (6)’s daughter</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>–</bibl>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>Ibn Hishām,Leben Muhammed’s, 353</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn9"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn10"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn9" n="2"> She appears in this story of her nephew’s conversion from Judaism to Islam, see Introduction 6.1.3. This implies that she was Jewish.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn10" n="3"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Ribāb-رباب">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn11"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Ribb-Vol-4-A_F" n="رباب">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e154-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Ribāb-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">رباب</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Ribāb</persName>
                     <persName>الرباب<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn12"/>
                     </persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>ÍÁrith (10)’s daughter, Íabiba (9)’s granddaughter, ÍuÒayn<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn13"/>(2), KhiyÁr<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn14"/>(2) and ÝUmar (15)’s mother</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>1. Ibn ÍabÐb,munammaq, 507; 2. MuÒÝab,Nasab, 200</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn15"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn16"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn12" n="2"> Appears in the text with the Arabic definite article ال, see Introduction 2.5.1.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn13" n="3"> See Lecker, JSAI 10 (1987) 21 and Ibn Ḥabīb, munammaq, 507.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn14" n="4"> See Lecker, JSAI 10 (1987) 25 and Ibn Ḥabīb, munammaq, 507.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn15" n="5"> Her mother was of noble Jewish descent. In Arabic – وأمها شريفة يهودية. </note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn16" n="6"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e213-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Ribāb-2">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">رباب</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Ribāb</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Kaʿb (9)’s daughter, Ḥusayl (1)’s wife, Saʿd (5), Mudlij (1), Safwān (1) and Laylā (1)’s mother</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ibn Saʿd,Ṭabaqāt, VII, 317; VIII, 320</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>Muslim convert<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn17"/>P:Medina</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>6thC CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn18"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn17" n="7"> Described in 320 as اسلمت الرباب (converted to Islam). That she was Jewish before, is Lecker’s assumption, but see Introduction 5.1.3.3.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn18" n="8"> Her children were contemporaries of Muḥammad, see Introduction 8.3.3.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Rayḥāna-ريحانة">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn19"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Rayna-Vol-4-A_F" n="ريحانة">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e262-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Rayḥāna-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">ريحانة</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Rayḥāna</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>ʿUmar (10)’s daughter</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>– S: Ibn Hishām,Leben Muhammed’s, 693</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn20"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn21"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn20" n="2"> Described in the text as clinging to Judaism (اليهودية), after her capture, see Introduction 6.1.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn21" n="3"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e291-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Rayḥāna-2">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">ريحانة</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Rayḥāna</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Zayd (11)’s daughter, Ḥakam (1)’s widow, of the Banū al-Naḍīr<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn22"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ṭabarī, iii, 2432</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn23"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn24"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn22" n="4"> In Arabic – من بنو النضير. She was married to al-Ḥakam of the Banū Qurayẓa. For that reason some genealogists traced her pedigree back to the Banū Qurayẓa, see Ṭabarī, ibid.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn23" n="5"> Belonged to the Banū al-Naḍīr, see Introduction 6.1.1.1.2.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn24" n="6"> Was married to Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Zaynab-زينب">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn25"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Zaynab-Vol-4-A_F" n="زينب">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e340-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Zaynab-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">زينب</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Zaynab</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Ḥārith (8)’s daughter, Shalum (1)’s wife</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>–</bibl>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>Ibn Hishām,Leben Muhammed’s, 764</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn26"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn27"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn26" n="2"> Her husband was found in a long list of names which is included in the chapter اسماء الاعداء من يهود (the names of the Jewish adversaries), see Ibn Hishām, Leben Muhammed’s, 351-2, and Introduction 6.1.1. In this episode we are informed that after the downfall of the Jews of Khaybar she attempted to poison the Prophet. Obviously she was Jewish. </note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn27" n="3"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Shuʿathāʾ-شعثاء">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn28"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Shuath-Vol-4-A_F" n="شعثاء">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e386-person"
                          n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Shuʿathāʾ-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">شعثاء</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Shuʿathāʾ</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>ʿUmar (16)’s daughter</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ibn ThābitDiwān, II, 208</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn29"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-Islamic<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn30"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn29" n="2"> Described in the text as من يهود (of the Jews), see Introduction 6.1.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn30" n="3"> She is mentionend in a poem which describes pre-Islamic Medina. More cannot be said about her.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Shamsam-شمسم">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn31"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Shamsam-Vol-4-A_F" n="شمسم">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e429-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Shamsam-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">شمسم</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Shamsam</persName>
                     <persName>שמסם<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn32"/>
                     </persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Šahrām (1)’s wife</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>Dedicatory inscription, Ḥimyar</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>CIS4/2, 543</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn33"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn34"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn32" n="2"> In Sabaitic Script, see Introduction 2.8.4.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn33" n="3"> The inscription is dedicated to ישראל ואלההמו רב יהד (Israel and its God, Lord of the Jews), see Introduction 6.1.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn34" n="4"> The inscription is not dated. Late antique date assumed, see Introduction 8.4.3</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Ṣaʿba-صعبة">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn35"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="aba-Vol-4-A_F" n="صعبة">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e474-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Ṣaʿba-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">صعبة</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Ṣaʿba</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Khālid (2)’s daughter, Tuwayt (1)’s mother<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn36"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ibn al-Kalbī,jamharat al-nasab, 69</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>Jew?<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn37"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre- 632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn38"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn36" n="2"> Her pedigree is not clear, see Lecker, MJP, 52 and n. 8, and see Introduction 6.1.2. She was married (successively) to two Qurayshī men: Asad b. ʿAbd al-ʿUzza and after his death she married his son Habīb b. Asad b. ʿAbd al-ʿUzza, see Introduction 6.1.1.1.5.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn37" n="3"> Maybe Ibn Ḥabīb, munammaq, 507, refers to her as من يهود الانسار (of the Jewish Ansār), see Introduction 6.1 and Lecker, JSAI 10 (1987) 26, but see also Introduction 5.3.1.1. </note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn38" n="4"> If she was of the Anṣār (‘the helpers’) of Muḥammad in Medina (see previous note), she his contemporary, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Ṣafīya-صفية">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn39"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="afya-Vol-4-A_F" n="صفية">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e529-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Ṣafīya-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">صفية</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Ṣafīya</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Ḥuyayy (1) and Barrah (1)’s daughter, Muḥammad’s wife<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn40"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ibn Hishām,Leben Muhammed’s, 354</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>Muslim convert<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn41"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn42"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn40" n="2"> Her marriage to Muḥammad is described in Ibn Hishām, Leben Muhammed’s, 766.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn41" n="3"> See ibid., and Introduction 6.1.3.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn42" n="4"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e570-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Ṣafīya-2">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">صفية</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Ṣafīya</persName>
                     <persName>
                        <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn43"/>
                     </persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Ḥafiẓ (1)’s daughter, the Prophet’s jār<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn44"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>–</bibl>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>Leveen,JQR16 (1925-6) 402</note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>Muslim convert?<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn45"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Early Pre-632 CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn46"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn43" n="5"> In Judeo-Arabic, see Introduction 2.8.7. The Hebrew צ can stand for the Arabic ص or ض, see Blau, Judaeo-Arabic (1965).</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn44" n="6"> In Judeo-Arabic – גאריה אלנבי. Leveen, JQR 16, suggests that this stands for the masculine form “Jār” (جار), which is a “neighbor” who stands under the protection of a certain tribe,” in this case under the protection of the Prophet himself, see Lecerf EI2 2, 558. Perhaps the author of this composition intended to refer to the previous woman (Ṣafīya [1]), see Introduction 2.8.7.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn45" n="7"> Her father is described as having converted to Islam האולו הם אלי' אלדין גאו אליה ואסלמו עלי ידיה לילא יציב ישראל שי (These were they who came to him [Muḥammad] and adopted Islam in his presence in order that no harm might befalls Israel). Probably she did too, see Introduction 6.1.3.1.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn46" n="8"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Fāṭima-فاطمة">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn47"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Fima-Vol-4-A_F" n="فاطمة">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e636-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Fāṭima-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">فاطمة</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Fāṭima</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Murr (1)’s daughter, soothsayer, of the people of Tabālah<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn48"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ṭabarī, i, 1079</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>Proselyte<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn49"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>6thC CE<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn50"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn48" n="2"> In Arabic – كاهنة ... من اهل تبالة.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn49" n="3"> In Arabic – متهودة, see Introduction 6.1.2.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn50" n="4"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad’s father, see Introduction 8.3.3.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
