                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn66" n="2"> Lecker, QdSA 11 (1993) 158, assumes that she was Jewish since her husband was a former Jew and converted to Islam, see Introduction 6.1.3. Also her mother is described as اسلمت الرباب (converted to Islam). That she was Jewish before, is Lecker’s assumption, but see Introduction 5.1.3.3.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn67" n="3"> Was a contemporary of Muḥammad, who died in this year, see Introduction 8.3.2.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
            <ab type="name" n="Hirr-هر">
               <ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn68"/>
               <listPerson xml:id="Hirr-Vol-4-A_F" n="هر">
                  <person xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-d8e895-person" n="Vol-4-A_F-Arabic-Females-Hirr-1">
                     <sex cert="high">F</sex>
                     <persName type="lemma">هر</persName>
                     <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Hirr</persName>
                     <persName>–</persName>
                     <state type="desc">
                        <note>Yāmin (2)’s daughter, Mawraq (1)’s sister, “harlot”<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn69"/>
                        </note>
                     </state>
                     <state type="provenance">
                        <note>–</note>
                     </state>
                     <bibl>Ibn Ḥabīb,muḥabbar, 185</bibl>
                     <state type="addl-Descr">
                        <note>–<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn70"/>P:Arab. Pen.</note>
                     </state>
                     <floruit>Pre-Islamic<ref type="note" corresp="#Vol-4-A_F-ftn71"/>
                     </floruit>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn69" n="2"> Her name “became synonymous with prostitution, and people said: more whoring than Hirr” (يضرب بها المثل في الزنا فيقال "أزنى من هر"). Many harlots are mentioned in the sources as longing for the death of the Prophet. For many of them it is not clear whether they were prostitutes in the common sence of the word. It is likely that these definitions are invective. It is also said about her that “immoral people used to visit her in the Jāhiliyya in turn to commit sinful acts” وكان الفساك يتناوبونها للفسق في الجاهلية, see Zamakhsharī, al-mustaqṣā, 1:150. See also Lecker, JAOS 115 (1995) 648.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn70" n="3"> In Arabic – اليهودية.</note>
                     <note xml:id="Vol-4-A_F-ftn71" n="4"> The sources describe her clients as of the Jāhiliyya, i.e. pre-Islamic.</note>
                  </person>
               </listPerson>
            </ab>
